hook.real_world_problem:
Your Spring Boot app is running. But nothing can talk to it — there's no HTTP interface. You need to expose your ProductService over the network:

```
GET  /api/products         → list all products
GET  /api/products/P001   → get one product
POST /api/products         → create a new product
PUT  /api/products/P001   → update a product
DELETE /api/products/P001 → delete a product
```

**Without REST controllers:**
```java
// None of these requests work — Spring doesn't know how to handle HTTP yet
```

**With @RestController:**
```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/products")
public class ProductController {

    @GetMapping
    public List<Product> getAll() {
        return service.findAll();  // Spring serializes to JSON automatically!
    }

    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<Product> getById(@PathVariable String id) {
        return service.findById(id)
            .map(ResponseEntity::ok)           // 200 OK + product as JSON
            .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());  // 404 Not Found
    }

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<Product> create(@RequestBody Product product) {
        Product saved = service.save(product);
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(saved);  // 201 Created
    }
}
```

GET, POST, PUT, DELETE — all mapped. JSON in, JSON out. Correct status codes. This is what every Java backend developer writes every day.

concept_explanation.restcontroller_basics:
**@RestController — the HTTP handler class:**

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import org.springframework.http.*;
import java.util.*;

@RestController                       // @Controller + @ResponseBody
@RequestMapping("/api/products")      // base URL for all methods in this class
public class ProductController {

    private final ProductService service;

    ProductController(ProductService service) {  // constructor injection
        this.service = service;
    }

    // GET /api/products
    @GetMapping
    public List<Product> getAll() {
        return service.findAll();
        // Spring serializes List<Product> to JSON array automatically
        // HTTP 200 OK (default when you return a value)
    }
}
```

**@RestController = @Controller + @ResponseBody:**
- @Controller: marks this as a Spring MVC controller
- @ResponseBody: return values are written directly to the HTTP response body (as JSON)
- Without @ResponseBody, Spring would look for a view template (HTML) instead

